<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">29478381</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2018</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>19</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2018</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1543-2920</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>30</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2018</Year><Month>Aug</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Pediatric exercise science</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Pediatr Exerc Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Relationships Between Training Load, Sleep Duration, and Daily Well-Being and Recovery Measures in Youth Athletes.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>345</StartPage><EndPage>352</EndPage><MedlinePgn>345-352</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/pes.2017-0190</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE">To assess the relationships between training load, sleep duration, and 3 daily well-being, recovery, and fatigue measures in youth athletes.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS">Fifty-two youth athletes completed 3 maximal countermovement jumps (CMJs), a daily well-being questionnaire (DWB), the perceived recovery status scale (PRS), and provided details on their previous day's training loads (training) and self-reported sleep duration (sleep) on 4 weekdays over a 7-week period. Partial correlations, linear mixed models, and magnitude-based inferences were used to assess the relationships between the predictor variables (training and sleep) and the dependent variables (CMJ, DWB, and PRS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS">There was no relationship between CMJ and training (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;-.09; &#xb1;.06) or sleep (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;.01; &#xb1;.06). The DWB was correlated with sleep (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;.28; &#xb1;.05, small), but not training (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;-.05; &#xb1;.06). The PRS was correlated with training (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;-.23; &#xb1;.05, small), but not sleep (r&#x2009;=&#x2009;.12; &#xb1;.06). The DWB was sensitive to low sleep (d&#x2009;=&#x2009;-0.33; &#xb1;0.11) relative to moderate; PRS was sensitive to high (d&#x2009;=&#x2009;-0.36; &#xb1;0.11) and low (d&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.29; &#xb1;0.17) training relative to moderate.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS">The PRS is a simple tool to monitor the training response, but DWB may provide a greater understanding of the athlete's overall well-being. The CMJ was not associated with the training or sleep response in this population.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sawczuk</LastName><ForeName>Thomas</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>1 Leeds Beckett University and Queen Ethelburga's Collegiate.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jones</LastName><ForeName>Ben</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>2 Leeds Beckett University, Queen Ethelburga's Collegiate, Yorkshire Carnegie Rugby Club , and The Rugby Football League.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Scantlebury</LastName><ForeName>Sean</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>1 Leeds Beckett University and Queen Ethelburga's Collegiate.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Till</LastName><ForeName>Kevin</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>3 Leeds Beckett University, Yorkshire Carnegie Rugby Club , and Leeds Rhinos Rugby Club.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2018</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>24</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Pediatr Exer